body:
The GitHub REST API is one of the most powerful automation tools available to developers. You can create issues, manage files, trigger workflows, read repository data, and build entire developer tools — all programmatically. Here's how to get started.

## Authentication

Create a Personal Access Token (PAT) at github.com/settings/tokens. For most operations, you need `repo` scope.

```javascript
const headers = {
  Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.GH_TOKEN}`,
  Accept: 'application/vnd.github+json',
  'X-GitHub-Api-Version': '2022-11-28'
}
```

## Reading Repository Content

```javascript
async function getFile(owner, repo, path) {
  const res = await fetch(
    `https://api.github.com/repos/${owner}/${repo}/contents/${path}`,
    { headers }
  )
  const data = await res.json()
  // Content is base64 encoded
  return atob(data.content)
}
```

## Creating or Updating Files

This is the key operation for any content management system built on GitHub:

```javascript
async function upsertFile(owner, repo, path, content, message, sha = null) {
  const body = {
    message,
    content: btoa(content), // base64 encode
    branch: 'main'
  }
  if (sha) body.sha = sha // required for updates

  const res = await fetch(
    `https://api.github.com/repos/${owner}/${repo}/contents/${path}`,
    { method: 'PUT', headers, body: JSON.stringify(body) }
  )
  return res.json()
}
```

## Creating Issues Programmatically

```javascript
async function createIssue(owner, repo, title, body, labels = []) {
  const res = await fetch(
    `https://api.github.com/repos/${owner}/${repo}/issues`,
    {
      method: 'POST',
      headers,
      body: JSON.stringify({ title, body, labels })
    }
  )
  return res.json()
}
```

## Listing Commits

```javascript
async function getRecentCommits(owner, repo, limit = 10) {
  const res = await fetch(
    `https://api.github.com/repos/${owner}/${repo}/commits?per_page=${limit}`,
    { headers }
  )
  return res.json()
}
```

## Creating Branches

```javascript
async function createBranch(owner, repo, branchName, fromSha) {
  const res = await fetch(
    `https://api.github.com/repos/${owner}/${repo}/git/refs`,
    {
      method: 'POST',
      headers,
      body: JSON.stringify({
        ref: `refs/heads/${branchName}`,
        sha: fromSha
      })
    }
  )
  return res.json()
}
```

## Rate Limits

Authenticated requests get 5,000 requests/hour. For most automation tasks, this is more than enough. Check your remaining limit:

```javascript
const res = await fetch('https://api.github.com/rate_limit', { headers })
const { rate } = await res.json()
console.log(`${rate.remaining} requests remaining, resets at ${new Date(rate.reset * 1000)}`)
```

## Real-World Use Cases

- **CMS on GitHub:** Store content as JSON files, update them via API from an admin panel
- **Automated changelogs:** Create issues or PRs when deployments complete
- **Repository auditing:** Scan all repos for missing files (README, LICENSE, etc.)
- **Bot integrations:** Auto-label issues, assign reviewers, or close stale PRs
- **Content pipelines:** Push generated content directly to a repo for static site deployment

The GitHub API is the backbone of tools like MyAppAI — it lets you treat your repository as a database and your deployment pipeline as an API endpoint.
